{
  "doc_id": "1129",
  "text": "An interesting question is whether neuronal networks activated by cocaine are specific for drug-related behavior or whether they overlap with other engrams, such as those inducing behaviors driven by natural rewards. By studying the pattern of phasic neuronal firing in MSNs in the NAc, it was found that the selective encoding of natural rewards (food, water, or sucrose) involves largely distinct cells from those encoding cocaine, with only 20% of neurons responding to both cocaine and sucrose or water reinforcements [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] . Remarkably, convergent findings using different biomarkers reveal that 2%-5% of cells encode a putative cocaine engram, including deltaFosB immune labeling [CITATION_3] , Daun02 inactivation of c-Fos-expressing neurons [CITATION_4] , and the number of NAc MSNs exhibiting phasic activity NAc MSNs [CITATION_5] . Furthermore, the same relative proportion of NAc cells in the cocaine engram is reported between passive drug-context associations during sensitization and active cocaine self-administration and reinstatement [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] ).",
